<title>CDA Logic.</title>
<para0 id="p3-2" label="3-2" tocentry="1">
<?PUB TOCLEVEL="3" TEXT="3-2 Introduction."?>
<title>Introduction.</title>
<para>The following paragraphs provide information on the Theory of
Operation for the CDA Logic. Part information is also provided in
paragraph <?hotspot href="p3-2.2"?>3-2.2 Part Information<?endhotspot?>.</para>
<subpara1 id="p3-2.1" label="3-2.1" tocentry="1">
<?PUB TOCLEVEL="4" TEXT="3-2.1 Theory Of Operation."?>
<title>Theory Of Operation.</title>
<para>The CDA Logic CCA contains the commander and gunner circuitry
which generates the controls and status lights for various elements
of the CDA. It also contains most of the control logic modes for the
turret systems. It contains a power supply that provides + and - 15
VDC used to activate the azimuth and elevation servo valves and to
bias various circuits in the electronics. In addition, the CDA Logic
CCA generates control and annunciator signals for the fire control
system.</para>
<subpara2 id="p3-2.1.1" label="3-2.1.1" numbering="1" tocentry="1">
<?PUB TOCLEVEL="5" TEXT="3-2.1.1 CDA Logic Equipment Description."?>
<title>CDA Logic Equipment Description.</title>
<para>The CDA Logic CCA contains surface mount resistors, capacitors,
IC chips, diodes, transistors and relays. Connections to the CDA chassis
are made through the J1, J2 and J3 connectors.</para>
</subpara2>
</subpara1>
